text: Finally, a movie that dares to mock Nazis. I wonder how a movie like this got made in Hollywood, and I applaud the filmmakers for their bravery in challenging conventions and delivering an urgent message that has not yet been heard.  Oh, sorry, I was thinking of _The Great Dictator._ Since Nazism ceased to be politically relevant about 75 years ago, this movie either doesn't have a political message or it's a stupid and immoral message conflating modern-day non-violent conservatives and nationalists with National Socialist fanatic mass murderers. _The Great Dictator_ was a tremendous moral stand, _The Producers_ was a brave successful approach of a taboo subject, this is just satirizing the easiest possible target, one that is historical and no longer extant in any meaningful, influential sense.  Don't get me wrong, I enjoy making fun of Nazis and pointing out their tremendous evil, but with the current political climate I'm expecting this movie will at least be promoted as relevant to contemporary politics, which is to say it will portray center-right politicians like Donald Trump and Boris Johnson as somehow modern-day Nazis. Obviously not relevant since they're not starting wars, mass murdering millions of people, launching genocidal campaigns, are not totalitarians or authoritarians, are opposed to socialism, and are in charge of liberal democracies with fair and free elections and rule of law.  That said, with politics aside, I like Taika Waititi and the cinematography is very pretty to look at (nice and colorful with no obvious horrible color grading), so I'll probably enjoy this film as I did _Hunt for the Wilderpeople._ I don't mind Waikiki casting himself in whiteface as Adolf Hitler. He'll almost certainly be good in the role. Looks like fun. If I was a comedian, I'd relish playing a Nazi in a movie like this.

text: I'm attracted to this marvelously quirky movie.  In an odd, far-reaching way (and from a deep, psychological perspective), it harkens Dr Jordan Peterson's warnings/admonitions about man's capacity for malevolence (and from that, how to fortify yourself to possibly resist it).  Specifically, Peterson talks about how any one of us - including himself - would have most likely "fallen-in with the crowd" of being a Nazi or BrownShirt in Germany circa 1930s.  It's easy to try and see ourselves as a social and spiritual hero of the day - say, an Anne Frank, or Dietrich Bonhoeffer, or Oskar Schindler - but only the rarest of us would have such stout, brave constitution.  Most of us would have succumbed to the omnipotent psychological phenomenon and brainwashing.  Taika Waititi tackles this deep, personal struggle in his own quirky, humorous style through the eyes of the young protagonist, Jojo.  It's fascinating, really.  (And just for the record, I, too, fear that I would have fallen in with the crowd back then.  Groupthink can be a very powerful setting; it's a mental state that can only be truly and honestly assessed after-the-fact.)

text: Of course you'd need some populist shill like Johansson playing the objective and disillusioned "lawful good" character. Almost as if she wouldn't sacrifice her principles for comedic purposes, why her acting is so stiff and dreadful, and why she's an emotionless personality vacuum. Can't wait to yawn whenever she's on screen.  Don't want to be the guy to bring historical accuracy into a satirical comedy, but nazification was so severe, that a kid wouldn't dare question if it was a good time to be a Nazi or not; because it always was. Or at least, that's what the ministry of propaganda was feeding them. If you want people to understand the actual seriousness of the tone you're setting underneath all that comedy and for the political climate Germans lived in at the time; because I'd assume sending that message was your intention given the circumstances; you need to believe that your main character is also subjected to that propaganda. The mothers character would be willingly sending her son off to Hitler youth, putting up pictures of Nazi propaganda all over the house, and painting Hitler as the ideal husband in her own head. Infact, it's a wonder she would be single at all in Nazi Germany without a man keeping her secure. As sexist as it sounds, and I assume feminism and strong independent women is their intention, she should be on the street or desperately trying to find a husband. Not making her own way in the upper echelons of Nazi society. Giving a woman so much power without earning it actually downplays the sacrifices they made to get there, and only hides the real challenges women faced not just in Germany, but other places around the world too. With something for the character to face and accept or challenge, it becomes their redemption story; rather than a one dimensional "I'm a good guy now" plot. Or maybe I'm looking too much into it and it really is just a movie for kids, which sends very mixed messages.   Hold on a minute... I wonder how many parents will take their kids to see a comedy movie plastered in Nazi iconography? "Mommy mommy, i wanna see that Nazi movie!" ü§î

text: Loved this movie :D   I never had anything against Nazism or anything, never lived those times, all I know in reality the ideology is bad and the things they did were bad and we shouldn't repeat those things in future, and I know and understand why. But all that stuff was 70 years ago, and people from those times are mostly very very old or dead, yet there are people who get offended nowadays when black humor comes out as well as satire things related to Nazism and Hitler, it's as if those people lived through those times and were affected by it, yet they never did.  Personally I am very neutral and I like black/dark humor, and this movie, like it says, is incorporating satire thorough and might be hard for them to see this movie any different than offensive rather than humorous in some scenes.  Personally I don't understand those people, how anyone can get offended by it at all nowadays, it's like nobody is offended by Caesar or Napoleon, they were basically equal but oldschool, and people are almost glorifying those historically infamous people for what they could achieve back then. But nobody bats an eye on them, I could guess why, but not any of those possibilities are enough of a reason to why bother with something that was 70 years ago, and not with something that was hundreds and thousands of years ago.  Same thing with PewDiePie controversy when dumb media took things subjectively and not objectively, and does not understand satire things, neither jokes, and just does it for attention and clicks.  I do wonder how many people, who usually get offended by Nazi and Hitler memes, or satire things related to Nazism and Hitler, though about this movie or watched it and actually either enjoyed or hated.

text: I realised something about this trailer. My explanation will contain spoilers, so keep scrolling.       Okay. In the trailer, you see a 10 year old kid with his imaginary friend, Hitler. You think, "Wow, this is going to be funny." It's then when you go to see the movie, your expectations of the movie are cast aside for what the movie really shows. You see, the trailer was purposely done like this. It took most of the comedic parts of JoJo Rabbit, but it leaves out all the dark parts of the movie. The trailer tricks you, henceforth you could consider it Nazi propaganda considering the movie and how it tricks you of what you are thinking. It shows the happy times but excludes anything dark, just like the Nazi posters.  When you watch the film, in the beginning, it is all happy, funny. But then, it pulls a 180 and shows you that JoJo's mother was hanged because she promoted a free Germany without the Nazis. Near the end, Germany was invaded so then JoJo can really see what war is like. He becomes disillusioned with the Nazis and his previous beliefs. He returns home to Elsa, where after lying who won the war, he talks to Hitler. They have a brief argument where JoJo has enough and breaks their friendship. When JoJo and Elsa walk outside they can now dance. JoJo can now walk outside as a young boy, not a Nazi.
